  <div class="breadcrumb"><a onclick="showPage('home',null)">Home</a> › Chapter 9</div>
  <div class="chapter-hero"><div class="chapter-tag">Chapter 09</div><h1>Rentals</h1><p class="lead">Trike rental operations for registered Songa drivers. The web application is the management interface for hub managers to view, approve, dispatch, and close rentals.</p></div>
  <div class="doc-body">
    <h2 class="section-h2">9.1 Rental Fees</h2>
    <div class="field-list">
      <div class="field-item"><div class="field-name">Standard Daily Rate</div><div class="field-desc">Fixed daily fee set in the Rates Manager. The driver must have sufficient commission balance to match this rate before a rental can be booked.</div></div>
      <div class="field-item"><div class="field-name">Energy Consumption Charge</div><div class="field-desc">(Start Energy − End Energy) × Energy Rate (KSH/kWh). Start and end energy logged at dispatch and return. Once TCU integration is complete, values will be fetched directly from trike IoT data in real time.</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="info-box"><strong>Leased trikes:</strong> Drivers operating trikes on a lease arrangement are charged only for energy consumption — the standard daily rental rate does not apply to them.</div>
    <h2 class="section-h2">9.2 Rental Detail Page</h2>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page031_img080.jpeg" alt="Rental detail — KPI cards, vehicle info, energy consumption, and digital signature link" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Rental detail — KPI cards, vehicle info, energy consumption, and digital signature link</figcaption>
</figure>

    <p>Six dark green KPI cards: Total Cost (KSH) · Total Distance (km) · Trip Duration · Energy Consumed (kWh) · Pickup Location (Hub Station name) · Pickup and Drop-Off Time.</p>
    <p>Vehicle Information: Driver Name, Vehicle Number, Date, Odometer Start-End, Safety Checklist score (clickable), Received By (with link to digital signature captured at rental end), Max Speed indicator.</p>
    <p>Energy Consumption: Total Energy Fee (KSH), Batteries Assigned (expandable to view individual battery details), Total Energy Consumed (kWh), Amount per Wh (energy rate applied).</p>
    <h2 class="section-h2">9.3 Approval and Dispatch Flow</h2>
    <div class="step-list">
      <div class="step-item"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-body">Driver submits rental request via Mobile App</div></div>
      <div class="step-item"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-body">Request appears in Requests module (Management Centre) under the Rentals tab</div></div>
      <div class="step-item"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-body">Hub Manager reviews: driver, pickup/dropoff dates, expected run — then accepts or rejects</div></div>
      <div class="step-item"><div class="step-num">4</div><div class="step-body">On acceptance: Hub Manager assigns a trike and logs battery start energy → status changes to Dispatched</div></div>
      <div class="step-item"><div class="step-num">5</div><div class="step-body">Driver notified via SMS and in-app notification with assigned trike details and pricing</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
<!-- CH10 -->
<div class="chapter-page" id="page-ch10">

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page033_img085.jpeg" alt="Hub Energy Management — hub listing with energy production and storage KPIs" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Hub Energy Management — hub listing with energy production and storage KPIs</figcaption>
</figure>

  <div class="breadcrumb"><a onclick="showPage('home',null)">Home</a> › Chapter 10</div>
  <div class="chapter-hero"><div class="chapter-tag">Chapter 10</div><h1>Hub Energy Management</h1><p class="lead">Real-time energy monitoring and management for each hub station. All data originates from hardware — there are no manual inputs in this module on Songa.</p></div>
  <div class="doc-body">
    <h2 class="section-h2">10.1 Hub Detail Page — Four Primary Sections</h2>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page034_img088.jpeg" alt="Hub detail — Energy Production, Storage, Prediction, and Consumption sections" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Hub detail — Energy Production, Storage, Prediction, and Consumption sections</figcaption>
</figure>

    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Section</th><th>Key Metrics</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Energy Production</td><td>Today's weather (temperature, sunset time), Total Energy Produced (kWh), solar panel status (Active/Inactive with activation time), % self-powered from solar today. Direct hardware reading from the inverter.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Energy Storage</td><td>Total Energy Stored (kWh), Solar vs. Grid storage bar, % capacity utilised. Manage button → Supply Control Panel. Grid shows -- kWh where not connected.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Energy Prediction</td><td>Energy Needed (kWh) based on upcoming trips/sessions, Batteries Needed (count), Energy Available (kWh), Upcoming Trips and Sessions counts, % of predicted demand achievable. Prediction model uses trip distance, historical energy consumption, estimated cargo weight, and session type/duration.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Energy Consumption</td><td>Total Energy Consumed (kWh) for the day, with source breakdown bar and kWh values for Solar / Storage / Grid — including percentage contribution from each source.</td></tr>
    </table>
    <h2 class="section-h2">10.2 Sub-Station Cards</h2>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page035_img091.jpeg" alt="Sub-station cards — energy consumed and source breakdown per metered area" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Sub-station cards — energy consumed and source breakdown per metered area</figcaption>
</figure>

    <p>Below the aggregate section, individual sub-station cards are shown for metered areas of the hub: Cold Store, Charging Station, Freezer, Working Station (configured per hub). Each card shows energy consumed and a source breakdown bar (Storage / Solar / Grid) with kWh values and percentages.</p>
    <div class="info-box"><strong>Per-Meter Source Attribution:</strong> Antarctica has built a proprietary attribution layer. For each 1-minute interval, if only one source is active, 100% of that section's consumption is attributed to it. When solar and storage are simultaneously active, consumption is split proportionally by the hub-level source ratio at that exact moment. This is a derived value, not a direct hardware reading. Cron job sampling interval: 1 minute.</div>
    <h2 class="section-h2">10.3 Energy Distribution Graph</h2>

<figure class="doc-screenshot doc-screenshot-wide">
  <img src="img/page036_img094.png" alt="Hub Energy Distribution Graph — Solar vs. Storage consumption in 30-minute intervals" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Hub Energy Distribution Graph — Solar vs. Storage consumption in 30-minute intervals</figcaption>
</figure>

    <p>A line chart at the bottom of the hub detail page shows energy consumed over time in 30-minute intervals. Two lines: Solar (yellow) and Storage (blue). The chart plots the delta (change) per reading interval — not cumulative totals — making activity patterns immediately visible (morning ramp-up, peak hours, afternoon solar peaks). Data points are hoverable, showing exact timestamp and kWh value.</p>
    <h2 class="section-h2">10.4 Supply Control Panel</h2>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page037_img097.jpeg" alt="Supply Control Panel — per sub-station ON/OFF, Energy Requirement, Source, and Distribution sliders" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Supply Control Panel — per sub-station ON/OFF, Energy Requirement, Source, and Distribution sliders</figcaption>
</figure>

    <p>Accessed via the Manage button. Hub manager's interface for configuring energy distribution to each sub-station. Four sub-station cards shown side by side: Charging Station, Cold Storage, Freezer, Working Station.</p>
    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Control</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      <tr><td>ON/OFF Toggle</td><td>Remotely switches the sub-station on or off via IoT</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Energy Requirement</td><td>Input field for how much energy (kWh) this sub-station requires</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Energy Source</td><td>Checkboxes for Solar (available kWh shown), Storage (available kWh shown), Grid (Connected/Disconnected status)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Energy Distribution</td><td>Three sliders setting the % split between Solar, Storage, and Grid for this sub-station</td></tr>
    </table>
    <div class="info-box"><strong>Future state:</strong> The smart inverter will take all energy distribution decisions autonomously based on sub-station requirements and available sources, removing the need for manual configuration through the Supply Control Panel entirely.</div>
  </div>
</div>
<!-- CH11 -->
<div class="chapter-page" id="page-ch11">

<figure class="doc-screenshot doc-screenshot-wide">
  <img src="img/page038_img100.png" alt="Batteries listing — status badges, hub assignment, and IoT telemetry columns" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Batteries listing — status badges, hub assignment, and IoT telemetry columns</figcaption>
</figure>

  <div class="breadcrumb"><a onclick="showPage('home',null)">Home</a> › Chapter 11</div>
  <div class="chapter-hero"><div class="chapter-tag">Chapter 11</div><h1>Batteries</h1><p class="lead">The most strategically important asset in the Songa ecosystem. All batteries are owned by Songa and are the primary source of revenue.</p></div>
  <div class="doc-body">
    <h2 class="section-h2">11.1 Battery Statuses</h2>
    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Status</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
      <tr><td><span class="badge badge-blue">Hub Station</span></td><td>At assigned hub station, available for use</td></tr>
      <tr><td><span class="badge badge-green">On A Trip</span></td><td>Currently loaded onto a trike on an active aggregation trip</td></tr>
      <tr><td><span class="badge badge-amber">Dispatched</span></td><td>Dispatched on a rental</td></tr>
      <tr><td><span class="badge badge-gray">In Service</span></td><td>Undergoing maintenance</td></tr>
      <tr><td><span class="badge badge-red">In Transit</span></td><td>Being transferred between hubs. Current Hub differs from Permanent Hub.</td></tr>
    </table>
    <h2 class="section-h2">11.2 Battery Detail Page</h2>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page039_img103.jpeg" alt="Battery detail — live SOC bar, BMS telemetry, charge cycles, and battery swap history" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Battery detail — live SOC bar, BMS telemetry, charge cycles, and battery swap history</figcaption>
</figure>

    <p>Live IoT metrics: Sum Volt (total voltage across all cell strings), Current in amperes (negative = discharging), Battery % (SOC bar indicator).</p>
    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Specification</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Charge Cycles</td><td>Total full charge/discharge cycles completed — key indicator of battery health and remaining usable lifespan</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Diff. in Voltage</td><td>Spread between max and min cell voltages (mV). A growing differential indicates cell imbalance — an early sign of degradation.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Battery SOH</td><td>State of Health — remaining capacity relative to original specification, degrading over charge cycles</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Battery Strings</td><td>Number of individual cell strings within the battery pack</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Temperature</td><td>Battery pack temperature</td></tr>
    </table>
    <p>Also shows a Battery Swaps table (historical swap events: date/time, swap station, surveyor, energy % at swap, trike, driver, status) and a Live Location map derived from the trike it is loaded onto (via TCU) or the hub it is stationed at.</p>
    <h2 class="section-h2">11.3 IoT Data Stream</h2>
    <p>When a battery is in use on a trike, the Thingsboard timeseries feed contains two interleaved data types:</p>
    <div class="field-list">
      <div class="field-item"><div class="field-name">GPS readings</div><div class="field-desc">Latitude, longitude, satellite count, speed — updated approx. every 10–12 seconds</div></div>
      <div class="field-item"><div class="field-name">Battery BMS readings</div><div class="field-desc">Battery ID, capacity, current (i), SOC, two temperature readings (temp1, temp2), voltage (v) — alternating with GPS readings on different intervals</div></div>
    </div>
    <div class="info-box"><strong>Real-time reflection:</strong> All state changes on the IoT platform are immediately reflected on Songa. If a battery disconnects from a charger, its status updates instantly on the Songa platform.</div>
    <h2 class="section-h2">11.4 Add Battery — Form Fields</h2>
    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Field</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Registration No.</td><td>Physical registration identifier for the battery pack</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Tag Number</td><td>Songa's internal asset tag</td></tr>
      <tr><td>IoT Device ID</td><td>Links the battery to its IoT device profile for live telemetry. Required for BMS data to appear on the battery detail page.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Charger Type</td><td>Determines which smart chargers this battery is compatible with (Canbus or Non-Canbus)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Battery Type</td><td>The model/type. Different types have different capacities and SOC calculation parameters, affecting energy accounting accuracy.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hub Station</td><td>Permanent home hub assignment</td></tr>
    </table>

<figure class="doc-screenshot doc-screenshot-wide">
  <img src="img/page041_img108.png" alt="Battery detail page — full BMS telemetry, swap events table, and live location map" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Battery detail page — full BMS telemetry, swap events table, and live location map</figcaption>
</figure>

    <h2 class="section-h2">11.5 Battery Transfer — Request Batteries</h2>
    <p>Hub managers can request batteries from another hub via the Request Batteries form.</p>
    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Field</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Receiver Hub Station</td><td>The hub making the request — the hub that needs batteries</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Supplier Hub Station</td><td>The hub that will supply. Available Batteries count shown dynamically on selection.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Request Type</td><td><strong>Direct Handover</strong>: battery physically moved, complete on receipt. <strong>Swap</strong>: batteries exchanged; both sides must receive before transfer is complete.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>How Many Required?</td><td>Numeric input for the quantity of batteries needed</td></tr>
    </table>
    <p>On submission, affected batteries show <span class="badge badge-red">In Transit</span> status. Both Hub Managers (via web) and drivers on active trips (via Battery Ambulance flow on mobile) can initiate battery transfers.</p>
  </div>
</div>
<!-- CH12 -->
<div class="chapter-page" id="page-ch12">

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page043_img113.jpeg" alt="Chargers listing — Canbus/Non-Canbus types, availability status, and IoT device linkage" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Chargers listing — Canbus/Non-Canbus types, availability status, and IoT device linkage</figcaption>
</figure>

  <div class="breadcrumb"><a onclick="showPage('home',null)">Home</a> › Chapter 12</div>
  <div class="chapter-hero"><div class="chapter-tag">Chapter 12</div><h1>Chargers</h1><p class="lead">Smart charging infrastructure across hub stations. Chargers simultaneously charge batteries and provide real-time BMS data on the connected battery.</p></div>
  <div class="doc-body">
    <h2 class="section-h2">12.1 Charger Types</h2>
    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Type</th><th>Capabilities</th><th>Naming Convention</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Canbus</td><td>Full two-way BMS communication: SOC, voltage, temperature, charge rate</td><td><code>KSC-CAN-XXXX</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Non-Canbus</td><td>Charging only, limited telemetry</td><td><code>KSC-NCAN-XXXX</code></td></tr>
    </table>
    <p>Statuses: <span class="badge badge-green">Available</span> — ready to accept a battery · <span class="badge badge-amber">Charging</span> — battery connected and charging · <span class="badge badge-gray">Retired</span> — decommissioned.</p>
    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Current operational note:</strong> While TCU integration on trikes is being finalised, chargers are the primary reference for energy accounting. Pre-trip battery energy is logged when removed from the charger; post-trip energy logged on reconnection. The difference determines energy consumed and driver charge applied.</div>
    <h2 class="section-h2">12.2 Add Charger — Form Fields</h2>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page044_img116.jpeg" alt="Add A New Charger form — serial number, Thingsboard ID, type, and hub assignment" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Add A New Charger form — serial number, Thingsboard ID, type, and hub assignment</figcaption>
</figure>

    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Field</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Serial No.</td><td>Physical serial number of the charger unit</td></tr>
      <tr><td>KSC Tag No.</td><td>Songa's internal asset tag</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Thingsboard ID</td><td>The charger's device ID on the IoT platform — links the physical unit to its Node profile and enables live telemetry</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Charger Type</td><td>Canbus or Non-Canbus</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Current</td><td>Charging current rating (e.g. 10 Amps, 15 Amps)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hub Station</td><td>Permanent hub assignment</td></tr>
    </table>
    <h2 class="section-h2">12.3 IoT Platform — Charger Nodes</h2>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page045_img119.jpeg" alt="IoT Charger Nodes dashboard — green (active), dark (inactive), red (error) node states" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>IoT Charger Nodes dashboard — green (active), dark (inactive), red (error) node states</figcaption>
</figure>


<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page045_img120.jpeg" alt="Charger node telemetry — BMS serial number, SOC, SOH, cell difference, and MOSFET states" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Charger node telemetry — BMS serial number, SOC, SOH, cell difference, and MOSFET states</figcaption>
</figure>

    <p>Each hub has a dedicated Thingsboard dashboard displaying all Node states in real time: green = active, dark = inactive, red = Provision Error or Address Error. Up to 30 nodes per hub.</p>
    <p>Clicking a node opens full telemetry. The critical field is <strong>BMS Serial Number</strong> — the unique identifier of the battery connected to the charger. This is how the platform attributes live battery data to the correct battery record on Songa.</p>
    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Node Metric</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      <tr><td>BMS Serial Number</td><td>Unique BMS identifier of connected battery — links node to battery record on Songa</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Cell Difference</td><td>Voltage spread between highest and lowest cells (mV). Growing differential indicates cell imbalance.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Battery Cycles</td><td>Total full charge/discharge cycles completed — key battery health indicator</td></tr>
      <tr><td>C MosFETs / D MosFETs</td><td>Charge and discharge MOSFET states (1 = open, 0 = closed)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Battery SOC</td><td>Current state of charge as a percentage</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Battery SOH</td><td>State of health — remaining capacity relative to original specification</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Charger State</td><td>Toggle showing whether the charger is active. Controllable from the IoT dashboard.</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>
<!-- CH13 -->
<div class="chapter-page" id="page-ch13">

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page047_img125.jpeg" alt="Users — Drivers listing with status badges, hub filters, and three-dot actions" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Users — Drivers listing with status badges, hub filters, and three-dot actions</figcaption>
</figure>

  <div class="breadcrumb"><a onclick="showPage('home',null)">Home</a> › Chapter 13</div>
  <div class="chapter-hero"><div class="chapter-tag">Chapter 13</div><h1>Users</h1><p class="lead">Manages two categories: Drivers (who execute all field operations) and Partners — Farmers and Off-Takers. Every operational record is linked to one or both.</p></div>
  <div class="doc-body">
    <h2 class="section-h2">13.1 Drivers</h2>
    <h3 class="section-h3">Driver Detail Drawer — Four Sections</h3>
    <div class="field-list">
      <div class="field-item"><div class="field-name">General</div><div class="field-desc">Name, Gender, Contact Number, M-Pesa Number, Hub Station, Email. Wallet Balance shown as three pills: KSH balance (cash commission), kWh balance (energy credits), Rentals count.</div></div>
      <div class="field-item"><div class="field-name">License</div><div class="field-desc">Licence Number and Validity date. View License button shows uploaded licence photo. Validity colour-coded: green tick (valid), amber clock (expiring soon), red triangle (expired).</div></div>
      <div class="field-item"><div class="field-name">Performance Rating</div><div class="field-desc">Average star rating (out of 4) and total trips. View Feedback opens full feedback history.</div></div>
      <div class="field-item"><div class="field-name">Time-off</div><div class="field-desc">Available time-off for the month as a fraction (e.g. 2/4) and count of Pending time-off requests.</div></div>
    </div>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page048_img128.jpeg" alt="Driver row three-dot menu — feedback, time-off, suspend, and other actions" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Driver row three-dot menu — feedback, time-off, suspend, and other actions</figcaption>
</figure>


<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page048_img129.jpeg" alt="Driver detail drawer — General, License, Performance Rating, and Time-off sections" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Driver detail drawer — General, License, Performance Rating, and Time-off sections</figcaption>
</figure>

    <h3 class="section-h3">Driver Rating</h3>
    <p>Ratings entered via three-dot Driver Feedback action or through the trip summary on completion. Scale: up to four stars per interaction with optional comments. Submitting feedback at least once per week is mandatory for hub managers. All ratings and comments are stored historically against the driver's profile.</p>
    <h3 class="section-h3">Add Driver — Key Fields</h3>
    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Field</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      <tr><td>M-Pesa Number</td><td>Mobile money account for commission payments (+254). 'Same As Contact Number' checkbox available.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>License ID / Validity</td><td>Driving licence number and expiry date</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Licence Photo</td><td>PNG/JPEG upload, max 2MB</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Email ID</td><td>Login credential for the Mobile App. Invitation email with 24-hour OTP sent on creation. Status shows Signup Pending until onboarding is complete.</td></tr>
    </table>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page049_img132.jpeg" alt="Add Driver form — personal details, M-Pesa number, licence, and hub station" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Add Driver form — personal details, M-Pesa number, licence, and hub station</figcaption>
</figure>


<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page050_img136.jpeg" alt="Driver profile fields — wallet balance pills (KSH, kWh, Rentals) and licence validity indicator" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Driver profile fields — wallet balance pills (KSH, kWh, Rentals) and licence validity indicator</figcaption>
</figure>

    <h2 class="section-h2">13.2 Driver Calendar</h2>
    <p>Full week view of all registered drivers simultaneously. Each driver occupies a row; each day is a column. Calendar entries show: trip count (trike icon), session count, and pending time-off requests (shown in red).</p>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page051_img139.jpeg" alt="Driver Calendar — full week view with trip counts, session counts, and time-off indicators per driver" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Driver Calendar — full week view with trip counts, session counts, and time-off indicators per driver</figcaption>
</figure>

    <h3 class="section-h3">Time-Off Requests</h3>
    <p>Each request shows: requested date range, driver name, submission date/time, driver's note, and a conflict warning — number of trips assigned during the leave period. Actions: Reject (immediate) or Approve.</p>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page051_img140.jpeg" alt="Time-off request detail — conflict warning, driver notes, and requested date range" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Time-off request detail — conflict warning, driver notes, and requested date range</figcaption>
</figure>

    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Approval requires trip reassignment first.</strong> If trips are assigned during the leave period, a Re-assign Items modal appears. The hub manager must select a replacement driver. Approval is only confirmed once trips are reassigned — preventing coverage gaps.</div>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page052_img143.jpeg" alt="Re-assign Items modal — hub manager must reassign trips before approving driver leave" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Re-assign Items modal — hub manager must reassign trips before approving driver leave</figcaption>
</figure>

    <h2 class="section-h2">13.3 Partners (Farmers and Off-Takers)</h2>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page053_img146.jpeg" alt="Partners listing — Farmers and Off-Takers with QR code, M-Pesa, and approval status" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Partners listing — Farmers and Off-Takers with QR code, M-Pesa, and approval status</figcaption>
</figure>


<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page053_img147.jpeg" alt="Partner detail — farmer profile, collection point, and Power Africa toggle" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Partner detail — farmer profile, collection point, and Power Africa toggle</figcaption>
</figure>

    <p>Each registered partner receives a unique QR code on creation — used by drivers to identify them in the field. An Export as CSV button is available.</p>
    <p>Drivers can register new farmers directly from the Mobile App in the field. The entry flows to the web platform with Approval Pending status. The Hub Manager reviews and approves before the farmer is available for future operations.</p>
    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Field</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Role</td><td>Farmer or Off-Taker</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Collection Point</td><td>The farm location where this farmer is typically collected from on trips</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Power Africa</td><td>Toggle designating this partner as a Power Africa programme participant, enabling them to book Kilikawi sessions</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>
<!-- CH14 -->
<div class="chapter-page" id="page-ch14">

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page055_img152.jpeg" alt="Requests — USSD tab listing Transport, Session, and Purchase requests with status" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Requests — USSD tab listing Transport, Session, and Purchase requests with status</figcaption>
</figure>

  <div class="breadcrumb"><a onclick="showPage('home',null)">Home</a> › Chapter 14</div>
  <div class="chapter-hero"><div class="chapter-tag">Chapter 14</div><h1>Requests</h1><p class="lead">The web-side inbox for all inbound requests — from the USSD platform and from the Mobile App. Two tabs: USSD and Rentals.</p></div>
  <div class="doc-body">
    <div class="info-box"><strong>USSD code:</strong> The Songa USSD service is accessible by dialling <code>*384*385#</code>. Requests can be submitted by anyone — registered or not.</div>
    <h2 class="section-h2">14.1 USSD Request Types</h2>
    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Type</th><th>Description</th><th>On Acceptance</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Transport</td><td>On-demand trike transport — functions like a logistics booking service. Open to anyone. Requestor specifies cargo type, pickup time, origin/destination.</td><td>Hub Manager assigns trike and batteries</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Session</td><td>Farmers book a Kilikawi agri-tech service. Detail drawer shows session type, date, and time slot pre-filled from USSD input.</td><td>"Accept &amp; Create Session" opens the Create Session wizard with farmer details pre-populated. Hub Manager completes agent, asset, and battery assignment.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Purchase</td><td>Product purchase requests (feed, fertiliser) from anyone in hub areas. No post-purchase tracking on the platform — once accepted, request is closed.</td><td>Status → Accepted; Songa fulfils offline</td></tr>
    </table>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page056_img155.jpeg" alt="Transport Request detail drawer — cargo details, pick-up area, and trike/battery assignment" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Transport Request detail drawer — cargo details, pick-up area, and trike/battery assignment</figcaption>
</figure>


<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page057_img159.jpeg" alt="Session Request detail — session type, date, and time slot pre-filled from USSD input" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Session Request detail — session type, date, and time slot pre-filled from USSD input</figcaption>
</figure>

    <h2 class="section-h2">14.2 Rentals Requests</h2>
    <p>Rental requests submitted by registered drivers via the Mobile App. Detail drawer shows: Contact No., Pickup Time, Estimated Run (km), Pick-up From (hub station). On acceptance, the hub manager assigns a trike and batteries; driver notified via SMS and in-app notification.</p>
    <div class="info-box"><strong>Leased trikes:</strong> Drivers operating a leased trike are automatically assigned that specific trike. Only batteries are assigned at dispatch. Leased-trike drivers are charged for energy consumption only, not the standard daily rental rate.</div>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page058_img162.jpeg" alt="Rentals Requests listing — driver-submitted rental requests with status and expected run" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Rentals Requests listing — driver-submitted rental requests with status and expected run</figcaption>
</figure>


<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page058_img163.jpeg" alt="Rental Request detail drawer — pickup time, estimated run, and trike/battery assignment" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Rental Request detail drawer — pickup time, estimated run, and trike/battery assignment</figcaption>
</figure>

    <h2 class="section-h2">14.3 USSD Flow Summary</h2>
    <div class="flow">
      <div class="flow-step">Anyone dials *384*385#</div><div class="flow-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-step">Selects request type</div><div class="flow-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-step teal">Request created (Pending)</div><div class="flow-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-step">Hub Manager reviews</div><div class="flow-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-step teal">Accept / Reject</div><div class="flow-arrow">→</div>
      <div class="flow-step">SMS sent to requester</div>
    </div>

<figure class="doc-screenshot doc-screenshot-wide">
  <img src="img/page059_img166.png" alt="USSD Requests flow at a glance — full journey from dial-in to Hub Manager action" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>USSD Requests flow at a glance — full journey from dial-in to Hub Manager action</figcaption>
</figure>

  </div>
</div>
<!-- CH15 -->
<div class="chapter-page" id="page-ch15">

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page060_img169.jpeg" alt="Locations listing — hub stations, collection points, and delivery points with activity type badges" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Locations listing — hub stations, collection points, and delivery points with activity type badges</figcaption>
</figure>

  <div class="breadcrumb"><a onclick="showPage('home',null)">Home</a> › Chapter 15</div>
  <div class="chapter-hero"><div class="chapter-tag">Chapter 15</div><h1>Locations</h1><p class="lead">The foundational module. Every entity is ultimately associated with a location. All locations are nested under a hub station.</p></div>
  <div class="doc-body">
    <h2 class="section-h2">15.1 Activity Types</h2>
    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Activity</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      <tr><td><span class="badge badge-teal">Hub Station</span></td><td>The physical hub — anchor for all other entities</td></tr>
      <tr><td><span class="badge badge-green">Collection</span></td><td>Farm or pickup point for produce collection</td></tr>
      <tr><td><span class="badge badge-blue">Delivery</span></td><td>Off-taker or vendor location for produce delivery</td></tr>
      <tr><td><span class="badge badge-gray">Aggregation</span></td><td>Location involved in the aggregation flow</td></tr>
    </table>
    <h2 class="section-h2">15.2 Add Location — Form Fields</h2>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page061_img172.jpeg" alt="Add A New Location form — name, address, GPS coordinates, hub station, and activity type" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Add A New Location form — name, address, GPS coordinates, hub station, and activity type</figcaption>
</figure>

    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Field</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Name</td><td>Display name of the location</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Address</td><td>Street or area address</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Latitude / Longitude</td><td>GPS coordinates, entered manually</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hub Station</td><td>The hub to which this location is assigned</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Activity</td><td>Activity type: Hub Station, Collection, Delivery, or Aggregation</td></tr>
    </table>
    <h2 class="section-h2">15.3 Add Hub Station</h2>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page062_img175.jpeg" alt="Add A New Hub Station form — used to create hub stations as location entities" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Add A New Hub Station form — used to create hub stations as location entities</figcaption>
</figure>

    <p>Hub stations are created via a separate Add Hub Station button — distinct from Add Location. Form captures: Name, Address, Latitude, Longitude. No Activity field required — hubs are assigned their type automatically. Once created, the hub becomes available for assignment across all platform entities.</p>
  </div>
</div>
<!-- CH16 -->
<div class="chapter-page" id="page-ch16">

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page063_img178.jpeg" alt="Containers listing — Canister and Crate assets with QR codes and hub assignment" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Containers listing — Canister and Crate assets with QR codes and hub assignment</figcaption>
</figure>

  <div class="breadcrumb"><a onclick="showPage('home',null)">Home</a> › Chapter 16</div>
  <div class="chapter-hero"><div class="chapter-tag">Chapter 16</div><h1>Containers</h1><p class="lead">Manages canisters and crates — physical containers used to collect and transport produce on aggregation trips.</p></div>
  <div class="doc-body">
    <h2 class="section-h2">16.1 Overview</h2>
    <p>Containers are registered as Songa assets, assigned to a hub, and issued a QR code on creation. Two types: <span class="badge badge-teal">Canister</span> and <span class="badge badge-blue">Crate</span>.</p>
    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Field</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Container ID</td><td>Unique identifier (e.g. Canister-6, Crate23)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Container Type</td><td>Canister or Crate — colour-coded badge</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Permanent Hub Station</td><td>The hub to which the container is permanently assigned</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Current Association</td><td>Hub or asset the container is currently linked to</td></tr>
    </table>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page064_img181.jpeg" alt="Add A New Container form — container type, ID, and permanent hub station" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Add A New Container form — container type, ID, and permanent hub station</figcaption>
</figure>

    <h2 class="section-h2">16.2 Operational Role</h2>
    <p>Containers are assigned to trips at creation. When a trip starts on the Mobile App, the driver must <strong>mandatorily scan the canister or crate QR code</strong> before proceeding. During milk collection, the driver scans the specific canister for each farmer — maintaining per-canister, per-farmer traceability across the trip.</p>
    <div class="info-box"><strong>Spoilage attribution:</strong> If milk is found spoilt at delivery, the canister scan record identifies exactly which farmer's produce was in that container.</div>
  </div>
</div>
<!-- CH17 -->
<div class="chapter-page" id="page-ch17">

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page065_img184.jpeg" alt="Service listing — asset type, severity badge, description, and ERP completion date" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Service listing — asset type, severity badge, description, and ERP completion date</figcaption>
</figure>

  <div class="breadcrumb"><a onclick="showPage('home',null)">Home</a> › Chapter 17</div>
  <div class="chapter-hero"><div class="chapter-tag">Chapter 17</div><h1>Service</h1><p class="lead">Tracks maintenance and repair across all asset types — Trikes, Batteries, and Kilikawi agri-tech equipment. Songa initiates service records; the ERP system owns the financial truth and determines completion.</p></div>
  <div class="doc-body">
    <h2 class="section-h2">17.1 Service Listing Columns</h2>
    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Column</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Service ID</td><td>Sequential repair identifier (e.g. Repair-074). Referenced as Asset Repair ID on the ERP system.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Asset</td><td>Name and type of the asset under repair</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Severity</td><td><span class="badge badge-green">Low</span> · <span class="badge badge-amber">Medium</span> · <span class="badge badge-red">Serious</span> · <span class="badge badge-red">Critical</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Description</td><td>Free-text description of the reported issue</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Date of Completion</td><td>Set when the ERP system marks the repair complete. Blank while in progress.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Maintenance Report</td><td>Expandable dropdown — populated from ERP on completion (inventory used, cost, actions performed, issue description)</td></tr>
    </table>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page066_img187.jpeg" alt="Maintenance Details drawer — inventory used, repair cost, actions performed, and issue description from ERP" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Maintenance Details drawer — inventory used, repair cost, actions performed, and issue description from ERP</figcaption>
</figure>

    <h2 class="section-h2">17.2 Creating a Service Entry</h2>
    <p>Initiated via Add to Service from the asset's three-dot menu (listing) or detail page. On submission, the asset moves to Service status and a corresponding Asset Repair record is created automatically on the ERP system in Draft status.</p>
    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Field</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Severity</td><td>Low, Medium, Serious, or Critical</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Description</td><td>Free-text description of the issue</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hub Station</td><td>Pre-populated from the asset's assigned hub. Editable if the asset is being serviced at a different location.</td></tr>
    </table>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page067_img190.jpeg" alt="Create A New Service Entry — initiated from within the asset detail with severity and description fields" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Create A New Service Entry — initiated from within the asset detail with severity and description fields</figcaption>
</figure>


<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page067_img191.jpeg" alt="Service form — hub station pre-populated from asset assignment" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Service form — hub station pre-populated from asset assignment</figcaption>
</figure>


<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page068_img194.jpeg" alt="Stock Consumed During Repair — spare parts entry with item, warehouse, quantity, and cost" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Stock Consumed During Repair — spare parts entry with item, warehouse, quantity, and cost</figcaption>
</figure>


<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page068_img195.jpeg" alt="ERP Asset Repair record — Actions Performed, Issue Description, and completion flow" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>ERP Asset Repair record — Actions Performed, Issue Description, and completion flow</figcaption>
</figure>

    <h2 class="section-h2">17.3 ERP Completion Flow</h2>
    <div class="step-list">
      <div class="step-item"><div class="step-num">1</div><div class="step-body">ERP Asset Repair record created in <strong>Draft</strong> status automatically by Songa on service entry creation</div></div>
      <div class="step-item"><div class="step-num">2</div><div class="step-body">Operations team opens the record on ERPNext and fills <strong>Stock Consumed During Repair</strong> — entering spare parts: Item, Warehouse, Valuation Rate, Quantity, Total Value</div></div>
      <div class="step-item"><div class="step-num">3</div><div class="step-body"><strong>Actions Performed</strong> and <strong>Issue Description</strong> completed to document what was done and why</div></div>
      <div class="step-item"><div class="step-num">4</div><div class="step-body">Repair Status changed from <em>Pending</em> to <em>Completed</em> (or <em>Cancelled</em>) → Save</div></div>
      <div class="step-item"><div class="step-num">5</div><div class="step-body">On save: inventory data, total repair cost, actions performed, and issue description flow back to Songa via the Controller Layer middleware. Maintenance Details drawer is populated. Date of Completion is set. Asset status returns to available.</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
<!-- CH18 -->
<div class="chapter-page" id="page-ch18">

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page069_img198.jpeg" alt="Rates Manager — Commodity Rates listing with Payment, Collection, and Commission rates per hub" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Rates Manager — Commodity Rates listing with Payment, Collection, and Commission rates per hub</figcaption>
</figure>

  <div class="breadcrumb"><a onclick="showPage('home',null)">Home</a> › Chapter 18</div>
  <div class="chapter-hero"><div class="chapter-tag">Chapter 18</div><h1>Rates Manager</h1><p class="lead">The financial configuration backbone. Every driver charge, farmer payment, off-taker collection, and driver commission is governed by rates set here. All rates are hub-specific.</p></div>
  <div class="doc-body">
    <h2 class="section-h2">18.1 Commodity Rates</h2>
    <p>Commodities are defined here — not just their rates. A commodity created in this tab becomes available for selection when building trip stops in the Trips module.</p>
    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Rate</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Payment Rate</td><td>Amount paid to farmers per unit (KSH/kg for milk). Songa's cost of procurement from the supply side.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Collection Rate</td><td>Amount charged to off-takers per unit for delivered produce. Songa's revenue from the demand side. The margin between Collection Rate and Payment Rate is Songa's gross margin on aggregation.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Commission Rate</td><td>Amount paid to drivers per unit of commodity successfully collected and delivered on aggregation trips.</td></tr>
    </table>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page070_img201.jpeg" alt="Add A New Commodity form — commodity name, payment rate, collection rate, and commission rate" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Add A New Commodity form — commodity name, payment rate, collection rate, and commission rate</figcaption>
</figure>

    <div class="info-box"><strong>Commodity scope:</strong> Rates are set per commodity per hub. The same commodity (e.g. Milk) can have different payment and collection rates at different hub stations.</div>
    <h2 class="section-h2">18.2 Energy Rates</h2>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page071_img204.jpeg" alt="Energy Rates listing — per-kWh charges by battery type, hub, and operation type" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Energy Rates listing — per-kWh charges by battery type, hub, and operation type</figcaption>
</figure>


<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page071_img205.jpeg" alt="Add Energy Rate form — battery type, hub station, operation type, and KSH/kWh rate" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Add Energy Rate form — battery type, hub station, operation type, and KSH/kWh rate</figcaption>
</figure>

    <p>Configures what drivers are charged per kWh consumed across all three operation types. Energy is Songa's primary revenue stream — calculated as (Start Energy − End Energy) × Energy Rate. Each combination of Battery Type, Hub Station, and Operation Type has its own rate record.</p>
    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Field</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Battery Type</td><td>Battery model (e.g. Fjshoan, Acceleron) — different battery types have different energy density and efficiency profiles</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Hub Station</td><td>Hub for which this rate applies</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Operation Type</td><td>Trip, Session, or Rental</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Energy Rate</td><td>Rate in KSH per kWh consumed</td></tr>
    </table>
    <h2 class="section-h2">18.3 Agri-Tech (Agent Commission)</h2>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page072_img208.jpeg" alt="Agri-Tech Commission Rates listing — hourly agent commission by hub station" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Agri-Tech Commission Rates listing — hourly agent commission by hub station</figcaption>
</figure>


<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page072_img209.jpeg" alt="Add Agri-Tech Commission Rate form — hub station and KSH/hour rate" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Add Agri-Tech Commission Rate form — hub station and KSH/hour rate</figcaption>
</figure>

    <p>Configures the hourly commission rate earned by agents for conducting Kilikawi sessions. This is what the agent earns — not the cost charged to farmers. Rate is set per hub and applies across all session activity types at that hub.</p>
    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Field</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      <tr><td>Hub Station</td><td>Hub for which this agent commission rate applies</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Commission Rate</td><td>KSH per hour of session conducted</td></tr>
    </table>
  </div>
</div>
<!-- CH19 -->
<div class="chapter-page" id="page-ch19">

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page074_img214.jpeg" alt="Revenue Manager — Payments tab with Amount Due to Farmers and Drivers KPI cards" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Revenue Manager — Payments tab with Amount Due to Farmers and Drivers KPI cards</figcaption>
</figure>

  <div class="breadcrumb"><a onclick="showPage('home',null)">Home</a> › Chapter 19</div>
  <div class="chapter-hero"><div class="chapter-tag">Chapter 19</div><h1>Revenue Manager</h1><p class="lead">Translates all operational activity into financial records. Two tabs: Payments (outgoing — to farmers and drivers) and Collections (incoming — from off-takers).</p></div>
  <div class="doc-body">
    <h2 class="section-h2">19.1 Payments — Farmers</h2>
    <p>KPI cards: Amount Due To Drivers · Amount Due To Farmers · Total Amount Paid To Farmers · Total Commission Paid To Drivers.</p>
    <p>Farmer detail page: trip-by-trip ledger — Date, Trip ID, Commodity, Total Weight, Rate (KSH/unit), Amount/Commodity, Total Amount. A Transaction History drawer shows all actual payment transactions made to this farmer (date, amount, reference).</p>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page075_img217.jpeg" alt="Farmer payment detail — trip-by-trip collection ledger and payment summary" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Farmer payment detail — trip-by-trip collection ledger and payment summary</figcaption>
</figure>


<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page075_img218.jpeg" alt="Farmer transaction history — actual payment dates, amounts, and M-Pesa references" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Farmer transaction history — actual payment dates, amounts, and M-Pesa references</figcaption>
</figure>

    <div class="info-box"><strong>Payments cycle:</strong> Every Wednesday, Songa pushes aggregated trip data to the ERP system. A purchase invoice is generated per farmer for the amount owed. On ERP approval, the payment is confirmed, the farmer's Total Amount Due is reduced, and the transaction is logged in their history.</div>
    <h2 class="section-h2">19.2 Driver Commission Algorithm</h2>
    <p>Commission is calculated weekly and credited to driver wallets on ERP approval. The algorithm is hub-level and trip-proportional — not a simple per-kg rate applied directly to each driver's weight:</p>
    <table class="doc-table">
      <tr><th>Step</th><th>Logic</th></tr>
      <tr><td>1</td><td>Calculate total weight delivered at the hub for the week</td></tr>
      <tr><td>2</td><td>Divide by 7 → average daily weight at hub level</td></tr>
      <tr><td>3</td><td>Calculate total trips at hub for the week; divide by 7 → average daily trips</td></tr>
      <tr><td>4</td><td>Average daily weight ÷ average daily trips = weight per trip (hub average)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>5</td><td>Fetch Commission Rate (KSH/unit) for commodity and hub from Rates Manager</td></tr>
      <tr><td>6</td><td>Count the individual driver's total trips in the period</td></tr>
      <tr><td>7</td><td>Pre-deduction commission = driver trips × weight per trip × commission rate</td></tr>
      <tr><td>8</td><td><strong>Spoilt milk deduction:</strong> if spoilt milk value &gt; commission ÷ 2, deduct commission ÷ 2 (capped at half). If spoilt milk value ≤ commission ÷ 2, deduct the full spoilt milk value. Spoilt milk valued at Collection Rate, not Payment Rate.</td></tr>
    </table>

<figure class="doc-screenshot doc-screenshot-wide">
  <img src="img/page077_img223.png" alt="Driver Commission Logic at a glance — hub-level weekly calculation visualised" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Driver Commission Logic at a glance — hub-level weekly calculation visualised</figcaption>
</figure>

    <h3 class="section-h3">ERP Commission Flow</h3>
    <p>A Driver Commission Ledger entry (format: <code>COM-LEG-YYYY-XXXXX</code>) is created per driver each week in the ERP's Songa App Integration workspace. Entries are created in Pending status and must be Approved via the Actions menu on ERPNext. On approval, commission is credited to the driver's KSH wallet balance on Songa.</p>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page078_img226.jpeg" alt="ERP Songa App Integration workspace — Driver Commission Ledger entries and approval flow" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>ERP Songa App Integration workspace — Driver Commission Ledger entries and approval flow</figcaption>
</figure>


<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page078_img227.jpeg" alt="ERP commission record detail — COM-LEG format, Pending to Approved status change" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>ERP commission record detail — COM-LEG format, Pending to Approved status change</figcaption>
</figure>

    <h2 class="section-h2">19.3 Collections</h2>

<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page079_img230.jpeg" alt="Off-Taker Collection History — trip-by-trip delivery ledger with commodity, weight, and rate" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Off-Taker Collection History — trip-by-trip delivery ledger with commodity, weight, and rate</figcaption>
</figure>


<figure class="doc-screenshot">
  <img src="img/page079_img231.jpeg" alt="Off-Taker detail — total amount due and collection history per off-taker" loading="lazy">
  <figcaption>Off-Taker detail — total amount due and collection history per off-taker</figcaption>
</figure>

    <p>Tracks revenue owed by off-takers for produce delivered during aggregation trips. Not connected to the ERP system — tracked on Songa directly. KPI cards: Amount Due From Partners · Total Amount Collected.</p>
    <p>Off-taker detail page shows a Collection History with trip-by-trip delivery ledger: Date · Trip ID · Commodity · Total Weight · Rate (Collection Rate from Rates Manager) · Amount · Total Amount Due.</p>
  </div>
</div>
